Checked versus unchecked — the rule.

Java is one of the few languages with checked exceptions. A checked exception is a compile time contract that says, this method might throw an io exception, and you must either catch it, or declare on your own method signature that you let it propagate. The keyword for the declaration is throws, written at the end of the method signature, followed by the exception type. If you do not handle a checked exception in one of those two ways, the code does not compile.

The rule of thumb the language designers gave was, use checked exceptions for recoverable conditions that a caller might reasonably handle. A file might not exist. A network call might fail. Use unchecked exceptions for programmer mistakes. You passed a negative size. You dereferenced a null. In practice, modern Java code leans unchecked. Checked exceptions do not compose well with lambdas and streams, because the abstract method on Function and Predicate and Consumer does not declare any checked exception. So if your lambda body would throw a checked exception, you have to catch it inside the lambda or wrap it. Most modern libraries lean toward unchecked, and you should too in new code.
